highlights.description: Moving to Madison from Milwaukee when I was 15 changed my whole like, "Wow, people live in a whole nother way"
People should not make decisions without having the people affected at the table
Here in Madison, people need to hear the raw and uncut stories; I don't feel true core honesty is in place
One thing that I can say that I like about Madison, as a father, is the sense of safety, even though I have some concerns
Community policing: when you have skin in the game, it changes the narrative
If you're of the community, you're not so quick to pull your gun and shoot someone
Should we require that police in high schools have kids themselves?
Until there are more teachers that look like some of the students, kids who want to be teachers go away from here because they know they will not be supported
What if we started hiring some of these moms to be in the schools instead of police?
Powerful response to a highlight via Hearth about policing in schools
Policing in schools: personal story about a loving response to out of control behavior
Problems with policing, response to cross-pollination
Highlight played about police in schools, useful to play before powerful response by Aron
Let's balance this out so that we don't have disparities in many of our institutions
Jerome, "those who are closest to the problems are closest to the solutions, especially in the criminal justice system." Those most affected need to be at the table for real, meaningful change.
Felix story about remedial v gifted class
Felix disagrees with police in schools because it takes money away from schools and devotes it to people who are not counselors.

Felix describes his experience in school where he was targeted as a student with behavioral problems and was recommended for ADHD testing and remedial classes over a gifted program... which is far too common in the assessment of students of color.
He had a moment in Madison that is not common in Milwaukee.  He and his friends had a smoke session with white folks they met on state street.
On the importance of demographics with respect to police oversight, victims, and positionality.
Bias in policing and its effects on police brutality.
On community policing as a better alternative.
Madison struggles to retain educators of color because there seems to be a lack of support for them.

Felix doesn't feel that the black excellence initiative is really supported throughout the school district, he feels there is backlash and that it is in part attributable to the current federal administration.
On the importance of representation and more specifically of marginalized groups.
It doesn't matter how well folks are doing post-incarceration you are still disenfranchised in society by not having a seat at the table (for the most part.)
Disparities against black Americans are visible in almost every sphere of life.
Describes his observation on folks in the South telling you directly that they are intolerant of people of color, whereas in Madison it is masked under the guise of a progressive liberal city.
Felix talks about what the role of police is (and isn't)
Those closest to the problem are best positioned to solve the problems.
